snippet.textDisplay:
Right away you hit the nail on the head: Kathleen Kennedy did not have a plan for how exactly this was going to play out. This is what happens when someone who does not know how to create a story or screenplay, but instead is a business manager, attempts to control a story. I would even blame the directors, who should know better and have more power, for not standing up to her or Iger, and saying "Hey, this is not going to work out. We need a plan. We can't just keep changing ideas on a whim to fit the current atmosphere. Stories don't work this way. It doesn't make any sense."


There is just a gaping difference between Disney's vision of Star Wars and Lucas'. Personally, I'm kinda glad that Disney failed in that respect. It goes to show that buying a franchise doesn't immediately make a company an instant winner or gatekeeper to all the lore of that series. You can't buy creativity when the core of the company doesn't appreciate it or know how to properly use it (as evidenced by their abolishing of the EU). I had a bad feeling about the selling of Star Wars to Disney right from the get go, but am still unhappy that it ended like this with so many fans, like myself, turned away from it. I haven't gone to see, or bought, any of the Disney Star Wars movies, mostly thanks to reviewers like you, AngryJoe, that gave honest opinions about what it was really like. The only thing Disney has produced so far that I am even remotely intrigued about is the Mandalorian show. However I am terrified that my favorite faction, the Mandalorians, will just have their lore gutted like everything else Disney has touched.

snippet.textDisplay:
Stop giving JJ a pass. You said right at the beginning, talking about Kathleen Kennedy, that they started the trilogy without a plan. That means that all the stuff that JJ did in TFA, all the secrets and hints, all of that was done without a plan. JJ wrote a mysterious parentage, a "good question for another time", the destruction of the new Jedi Academy, the turning of Ben Solo, the defeat of Kylo Ren, the mysterious villain, and all the rest without a goddamn plan. He didn't know who Rey's parents were. He didn't have a reason for why she was so unreasonably overpowered and perfect. It was just an empty mystery box.

JJ is a parasite. He puts beautifully wrapped Xmas boxes under the tree, but they are all completely empty. He writes in a way that takes advantage of the fact that when we see those boxes under the tree, we expect there to be presents in them. We are there for the presents, and that's what he charges us for and leads us to believe we'll be getting.

But we get nothing.

You're incorrect about the Emperor's power. They were:
1. Sitting on the Sith's nexus of Darkside power. So his powers were far more amplified.
2. Palpatine in the novels, etc, was a Sith Sorcerer. He was one of the strongest Sith in history.
3. The way he was brought back was pretty similar to the old novels, in which he was resurrected even stronger than before.

It would have made more sense if the plot was based around him using an Essense Transfer to Rey's body, if she was a Palpatine.

To be honest, the Palpatine we see in the movie is far closer to the Legends original content than we've seen him before. It feels like they took aspects from that and mixed it into the movie.

snippet.textDisplay: I challenge you to go back and look at the Original Trilogy and analyze and breakdown each one of those films.  You can say the very same things that your saying now.  But when we watched the Originals we weren't critics, we were just transported to a fun fictional place.  I'm hope that these reviews aren't read or taken literally by young viewers.  We the fans influence what can be accepted and we should not ruin this trilogy for the generation that only have seen these films.  Last Jedi was complicated.  Younger people do not need things to sink in.  It has to be fast, to them this was fun and exciting.  To most, including my own, kids 6 to 17 find the originals to be boring.  They are more fascinated with snapchat videos and cat memes.  These angry rants seem selfish and truly shows that you cant have that wonderment and appreciation for just being there.  I remember how excited I was to see the rereleased Original trilogy.  To experience the movies in the Theater like my parents did.  I'm glad I was able to take my family and friends to  experience this.  Next time, dont take a pad of paper to take notes on a film.  Take someone you want to have fun and  experience the wonderment of going to the movies.  Not everything has to be Shakespeare for you.

snippet.textDisplay:
Just like to add some things amidst all this, it's something that I hear (also with other movies sometimes) quite often.
First is saying force powers in this movie wete pulled out of the writer's ass. Well, guess what, in the very first Star Wars they were made up too! Just because we didn't see it all in the original trilogy does that mean the limits were set in stone? I'm okay with new stuff. Maybe as time progresses the wielders learn more as they get experienced.
Second is about how you can't identify with a main character. I don't care about that! Sometimes I hear people say 'for who am I supposed to root for in this movie?'
Well may you don't! I can enjoy a movie even if every character is an asshole! I don't NEED to identify myself in the hero. Tell me the story and how it evolves, that's perfectly fine.
I agree with many of your points, but I actually enjoyed the movie. I would give it a 7 out of 10.
